wncaa <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/vaiseys/dav-course/main/Data/wncaa.csv")

Question 1

tourney_champ <- wncaa %>%
  filter(tourney_finish == "Champ") %>%
  group_by(school) %>%
  summarise(N = n()) %>%
  mutate(freq = N/ sum(N))

ggplot(data = tourney_champ,
       mapping = aes(x = N)) +
  geom_bar() +
  coord_flip()

The teams that have won the most tourneys are Tennessee and UConn.

Question 2

champ_names <- unique(tourney_champ$school)

winners <- wncaa %>% 
  filter(school %in% champ_names)

ggplot(data = winners,
       mapping = aes(x = seed, 
                     y = reorder(school, seed))) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(width = .2, alpha = .2)

The teams that were seeded the highest have played the against the

Question 4

winners_mean_sd <- winners %>% 
  group_by(school) %>% 
  summarize(across(where(is.numeric),
                   list(mean = mean,
                        sd = sd)))

ggplot(data = winners_mean_sd,
       mapping = aes(x = reorder(school, reg_percent_mean),
         y = reg_percent_mean)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, width = .2) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs( x = "School")
## Warning in geom_point(size = 2, width = 0.2): Ignoring unknown parameters:
## `width`

Texas, Purdue, USC, and Texas A&M have the lowest regualr seaons win average. Norte Dame, NC, Texas Tech, SC, Old Dominion, and Marylands regular season win average results are in the middle of the dataset. Tennessee, Stanford, Baylor, Louisiana Tech, and Uconn have the highest regular season win average. The results show that Uconn has the highest regular seasons win average across the seasons, and Texas A&M has the lowest. UConn is a bit of an outlier in this data set.

winners_mean_sd <- winners %>% 
  group_by(school) %>% 
  summarize(across(where(is.numeric),
                   list(mean = mean,
                        sd = sd)))

ggplot(data = winners_mean_sd,
       mapping = aes(x = reorder(school, reg_percent_mean),
         y = reg_percent_mean)) +
  geom_pointrange(mapping = aes(ymin = reg_percent_mean - reg_percent_sd,
                                ymax = reg_percent_mean + reg_percent_sd)) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs( x = "School")

Texas A&M has the narrowest interval meaning they had the smallest standard deviation.

winners_mean_sd <- winners %>% 
  group_by(school) %>% 
  summarize(across(where(is.numeric),
                   list(mean = mean,
                        sd = sd)))

ggplot(data = winners_mean_sd,
       mapping = aes(x = reorder(school, reg_percent_mean),
         y = reg_percent_mean)) +
  geom_linerange(mapping = aes(ymin = reg_percent_mean - reg_percent_sd,
                                ymax = reg_percent_mean + reg_percent_sd)) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs( x = "School")

I think using a geom_pointrange gives you more information because the point gives you both the median point as well as the range. It depends on what information you are looking for, to determine which graph is better for you.
